[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout]         # PAPER BODY TEXT:
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout]         ---
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout]         Introduction
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] In the past 10 years, AI has rapidly grown in the healthcare
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] sector. In the US, for example, over 100 new AI-driven med-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ical devices have been approved by the Food and Drug Ad-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ministration (FDA) every year since 2020. Although tech-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] niques for automating image processing and feature identi-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] fication have been developed and used since the 1990s, this
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] recent growth in the development of AI-driven devices has
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] been driven by developments in neural networks and trans-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] former models, the availability of more compute resources,
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] and increased adoption of electronic health records globally.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Copyright © 2025, Association for the Advancement of Artificial
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Intelligence (www.aaai.org). All rights reserved.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] AI-driven medical devices have been developed for a
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] number of different clinical purposes, including earlier de-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tection of abnormalities like tumors, improving efficiency
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] and clinician confidence by acting as a “second pair of
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] eyes”, better management of staff resources by triaging and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] prioritizing the most urgent cases, and even improving the
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] speed and quality of image generation. With the increased
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] accessibility and improved performance of large language
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] models (LLMs), the use of AI has also expanded to admin-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] istrative tasks like patient scheduling (Knight et al. 2023),
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] summarizing clinical notes (Van Veen et al. 2024), and pa-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tient messaging (Chen et al. 2024; Garcia et al. 2024). De-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] spite the positive potential of these systems, however, there
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] have been concerns regarding automation bias (Abdelwanis
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] et al. 2024; Dratsch et al. 2023), gender or racial biases
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] (Gichoya et al. 2022; Adam et al. 2022), patient privacy
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] (Murdoch 2021), worsened clinician burnout (Kwee and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Kwee 2021), and other risks.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Preceding the adoption of newer ‘AI’ systems, clinical de-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] cision support systems (CDSS) have been widely used in
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] hospitals. There are a number of studies on clinician atti-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tudes towards CDSSs (Pope et al. 2013), implementation
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] challenges they generate (Liberati et al. 2017; Ford et al.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 2021), and their impact on patient outcomes (Garg et al.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 2005). Recently, there have also been an increasing number
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] of qualitative studies exploring clinician attitudes towards
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] AI, including perceived benefits and concerns (Oremule et
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] al. 2024; Fazakarley et al. 2023; Nittas et al. 2025; Parikh et
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] al. 2022), and perspectives on how responsibility should be
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] distributed for AI outcomes (Laï, Brian, and Mamzer 2020;
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Van Cauwenberge et al. 2022).
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Scholars have also discussed regulatory (top-down) gov-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ernance challenges generated by AI in healthcare
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] (Palaniappan, Lin, and Vogel 2024; Ong et al. 2025; Gilbert
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Proceedings of the Eighth AAAI/ACM Conference on AI, Ethics, and Society (AIES 2025)
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 1018
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] et al. 2023; Castonguay et al. 2024). However, with the ex-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ception of a few recent studies (Nong, Hamasha, and Platt
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 2024; Chow, Lee, and Wu 2025) there is limited research on
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] how AI is currently being deployed and governed at individ-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ual hospitals. This ‘bottom-up’ aspect of governance is par-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ticularly interesting in the context of healthcare, as the
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] highly regulated nature of the sector has created complex
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] dynamics between stakeholders within different layers of
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] governance, including hospitals, professional societies, and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] regulators at the regional or national level. In our paper, we
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] build on an ‘institutional approach’ to healthcare govern-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ance (Abimbola et al. 2017), to explore the relationship be-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tween bottom-up and top-down approaches to AI govern-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ance.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] To that end, we conducted qualitative interviews with 22
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] participants involved in AI governance within radiology de-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] partments in the US and UK; focusing on this subspecialty
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] and these countries as they have the greatest maturity of AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] adoption (Castonguay et al. 2024; Allen et al. 2021; US
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Food and Drug Administration 2025). We conducted semi-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] structured qualitative interviews with radiologists, radiation
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] oncologists (also known as medical physicists and clinical
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] scientists), and researchers based in radiology departments;
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] prioritising individuals with experience on AI governance
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] committees within their hospital and/or within a medical
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] professional society. We also interviewed a small sample of
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] industry participants and regulators with experience in AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] development and governance. Across these interviews we
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] aimed to answer the following research questions: ( RQ1 )
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] What is the current state of adoption and governance of AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] in radiology departments in the US and UK? ( RQ2 ) How do
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] clinical staff in radiology perceive their role/responsibility
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] for AI-related outcomes? ( RQ3 ) Does AI pose unique chal-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] lenges at the intersection between bottom-up governance
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] and top-down rules? ( RQ4 ) What recommendations do ex-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] perts have for improving governance of AI going forward?
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Using abductive thematic analysis, we uncover the fol-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] lowing themes. First, we find variance in the types of gov-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ernance mechanisms designed at different hospitals, owing
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] to different perceptions of AI, availability of resources, and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] technical expertise. This finding suggests that the specialty-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] driven approach in medicine is increasingly at odds with the
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] deployment of AI across a wide range of contexts. Second,
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] our findings show that some clinicians have taken on addi-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tional AI-focused governance roles, often on a voluntary ba-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] sis, either within their own hospitals or as part of task groups
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] and working groups formed within professional bodies. We
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] discuss these roles within the context of ‘policy entrepre-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] neurs’ (Durant and Diehl 1989), while noting the unique
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] challenges that participants face in operating within deeply
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] hierarchical organizations, navigating power relations, and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] justifying their role. Third, we find that although partici-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] pants almost unanimously agreed that the clinician using an
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] AI device bears ultimate responsibility for patient outcomes,
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] there was ambivalence regarding who should be responsible
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] for ongoing performance evaluation of AI devices; suggest-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ing the practical risk of clinicians being placed in ‘moral
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] crumple zones’ (Elish 2019). Finally, our results demon-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] strate participants’ simultaneous desire for standardized
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] guidance on how to adopt AI, and robust local governance
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] measures tailored to unique patient populations; indicating
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] possible tensions between top-down and bottom-up ap-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] proaches towards AI governance.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Background and Theoretical Underpinning
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Prior to interviewing participants, we created a topic guide,
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] developing interview questions from theoretical frame-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] works on responsibility and institutional governance. Be-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] low, we provide some detail about these frameworks.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Figure 1: Overlapping layers of healthcare governance
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 1019
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Novel Responsibility Challenges Generated by AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Ever since Andreas Matthias coined the term “responsibility
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] gap,” (Matthias 2004) scholars at the intersection of AI eth-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ics, policy, and governance have been using this concept to
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] articulate the challenge of assigning responsibility for the
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] outcomes of AI systems (Coeckelbergh 2020; Nyholm
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 2018; Santoni de Sio and Mecacci 2021; Bleher and Braun
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 2022). In particular, the argument is that since machine
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] learning algorithms automate some aspects of decision-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] making, it is challenging to assign responsibility to the hu-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] man operators of such systems. This challenge can theoreti-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] cally create a ‘gap’, where no one is ultimately responsible
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] for AI outcomes despite society continuing to pay the cost
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] for its harmful impacts (Matthias 2004). On the other hand,
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] some scholars highlight the risk that ambiguity in responsi-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] bility attribution can lead to one person absorbing all the re-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] sponsibility for an AI outcome, thus falling within the
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ‘moral crumple zone’ (Elish 2019; Smith and Fotheringham
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 2020). Scholars also note that the increasingly complex sup-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ply chains involved with AI development and deployment
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] (Widder and Nafus 2023; Cobbe, Veale, and Singh 2023)
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] generate challenges for identifying which of the ‘many
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] hands’ (Coeckelbergh 2020; Nissenbaum 1996) should be
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] held accountable for AI-related outcomes.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Within the context of healthcare, although there has been
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] some theoretical work suggesting that AI systems used for
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] clinical decision-making generate novel challenges for as-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] signing responsibility (Bleher and Braun 2022), empirical
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] studies have shown the continued emphasis clinicians place
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] on having the ‘final responsibility’ over clinical outcomes
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] when using AI for decision support (Jones, Thornton, and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Wyatt 2023; Van Cauwenberge et al. 2022; Laï, Brian, and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Mamzer 2020). Thus, in our qualitative study, we aimed to
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] understand participants’ perceptions of their own responsi-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] bility for both AI use and governance within the hospital.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Relationship Between ‘Bottom-Up’ and ‘Top-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Down’ Governance
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] In our analysis of AI governance, we refer to both formal
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] regulations and legal liabilities, and informal guidelines
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] such as ethical codes of conduct, practice guidelines, and in-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] formal governance committees. Governance has historically
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] been one means of addressing ‘gaps’ in responsibility
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] emerging from the deployment of new innovations (Vallor
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] and Ganesh 2023). This can be done through forward-look-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ing assignation of responsibility, such as assignment of du-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ties, roles and offices to morally and legally answerable in-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] dividuals, or backward-looking inspection of how causal,
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] moral and legal responsibilities should be assigned. Because
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] healthcare is a heavily regulated field, with binding legal
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] and regulatory obligations, as well as an established culture
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] of responsibility and ethical norms at the individual, organ-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] izational, and professional level (Hajar 2017; Bryden and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Storey 2011; Nandi 2000; Beauchamp and Childress 1979),
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] there is already a precedent for robust forward and back-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ward-looking assignation of responsibility, with clearly de-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] lineated roles, hierarchies, and protocols for quality assur-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ance within hospitals (Jalilvand, Raeisi, and Shaarbafchiza-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] deh 2024; Liberatore and Nydick 2008; Esposito and Dal
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Canton 2014; Foy et al. 2020).
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] However, the different layers of healthcare governance
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] create complex dynamics for stakeholders governing AI use.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] On one hand, there are regulatory bodies, such as the FDA,
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] and the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Agency (MHRA) in the UK, which set requirements for
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] medical device testing before they are placed on the market.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] In addition, some regions have specific laws, such as regu-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] lations on the use of X-ray equipment within that region.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Within hospitals, hospital boards and administrators are le-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] gally responsible for monitoring quality and safety, but del-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] egate this authority to clinical committees or staff councils
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] (Jalilvand, Raeisi, and Shaarbafchizadeh 2024). Governance
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] also emerges at the level of professional societies, which are
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] often subspecialty-specific, and develop targeted practice
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] guidelines for adoption by individual hospital departments.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] A simplified diagram of these different relationships is pre-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] sented below in Figure 1.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] AI generates some novel governance challenges when
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] compared to previous technologies. For one, because the
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] performance of AI systems is so dependent on the data used
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] to train a given algorithm, performance can vary across dif-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ferent patient populations (Sahiner et al. 2023). Thus, regu-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] latory approval does not guarantee that an AI system will
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] perform well on a given hospital’s data. Currently, regula-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tory approvals are also restricted to ‘static’ systems that do
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] not evolve over time, generating risks that AI system perfor-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] mance degrades over time (Sahiner et al. 2023). In response
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] to these risks, in addition to subjecting AI medical devices
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] to thorough testing requirements prior to placing them on
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] the market, regulatory bodies like the FDA and the MHRA
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] have also begun developing guidance for reporting post-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] market performance, known as post-market surveillance.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Despite these interventions, however, regulatory bodies still
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] have limited oversight over the use of AI in clinical practice.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] For example, long regulatory approval times have incentiv-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ized companies to apply for approval in lower-risk catego-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ries, assuming that clinicians will use these systems differ-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ently ‘off-label’ (Krishnamoorthy, Sjoding, and Wiens
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 2024). To fill these gaps, there have been an overwhelming
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] number of professional societies, standards bodies, and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] other related organizations issuing guidelines on the clinical
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] adoption of AI (Brady et al. 2024; Hadjiiski et al. 2023; The
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Royal College of Radiologists 2024; British Medical Asso-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ciation 2024; American Medical Association 2024). Some
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] individual hospitals are also now developing processes and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] guidelines for adopting AI (Kim et al. 2023; Daye et al.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 2022).
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 1020
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Although our qualitative study is primarily concerned
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] with bottom-up governance, the intersection between vari-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ous layers of governance motivated us to explore an ‘insti-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tutional approach’ to governance, focusing on the relation-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ship between hard rules and emerging ‘building blocks’ at
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] the local level (Abimbola et al. 2017). To that end, our in-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] terview topic guide included questions related to local, pro-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] fessional, and regulatory governance. We discuss the inter-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] view methodology in more detail below.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Interview and Coding Methodology
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] The expert interview is commonly used in the social sci-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ences for exploratory analysis, obtaining of specialized
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] knowledge, or theory generation (Bogner, Littig, and Menz
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 2009). For our study, semi-structured interviews presented
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] advantages over other methods, such as surveys, because
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] they enabled a more in-depth understanding of individual
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] motivations and organizational dynamics. Additionally,
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] given the sensitive regulatory and legal landscape of the
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] healthcare sector, and the relatively early stage of AI adop-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tion and governance, information and rationales for hospi-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tal-specific AI governance measures would be difficult to
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] assess without consulting with experts who are involved
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] with implementing these measures on the ground.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Recruitment Strategy and Participant Summary
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Participant recruitment focused on ‘experts’, who defined as
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] individuals with experience using or governing AI in radiol-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ogy departments, including radiologists, radiation oncolo-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] gists (also known as medical physicists and clinical scien-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tists), and researchers. The field of radiology was chosen as
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] it is currently the most mature area of AI adoption in
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] healthcare (Allen et al. 2021). We interviewed participants
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] in the US and UK, as these countries currently lead in AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] development and adoption among OECD countries
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] (Castonguay et al. 2024). In addition to clinical participants,
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] we interviewed a subset of participants from regulatory and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] industry backgrounds, to explore the interaction between lo-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] cal, professional, and regulatory governance. Participants
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] were recruited through professional contacts, radiology and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] radiation oncology conferences, advertising on social me-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] dia, and snowball sampling (Vogt and Johnson 2015). All of
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] the clinicians (including those not involved with govern-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ance) had experience using AI in their day-to-day work. Ex-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] actly half of the participants were US-based and the other
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] half were UK-based. Roughly 2/3 were male, while 1/3 were
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] female (mirroring gender imbalances in radiology). The ma-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] jority of US participants (all but one) belonged to academic
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] medical centers, which are typically ‘early adopters’ of new
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] technologies (Faruki, Zane, and Wiler 2022), and only three
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] UK participants (representing 2 hospital systems) were
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] practicing at ‘Academic Health Science Centers’ (AHSCs).
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Interview Structure and Topic Guide
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Interviews were conducted by the primary author from
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] March 2024 – March 2025, for 45-60 minutes (each) on Mi-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] crosoft Teams. Two pilot interviews were conducted with
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] clinicians (one each from the US and UK) experienced with
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] using AI in their day-to-day practice. Questions were de-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] rived from the theoretical frameworks on responsibility and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] institutional governance presented above. The topic guide
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] was refined after pilot interviews and peer debriefing
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] (Lincoln, Guba, and Pilotta 1985) with co-authors. Partici-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] pants were asked questions about their background/training,
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] experiences and benefits/ concerns with using AI, individual
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] responsibility for AI outcomes, involvement in profes-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] sional/local governance (if applicable), thoughts on regula-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tory governance, and general recommendations on how AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] governance could be improved in radiology.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Coding and Analysis
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] We utilized abductive thematic analysis (Thompson 2022),
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] to undertake an iterative process of triangulating between
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] data and theoretical frameworks, also known as ‘theoretical
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] triangulation’ (Morse, Knafl, and Breitmayer 1991; Denzin
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 2017). All coding was done using the qualitative coding
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] software NVivo (14). The codebook was initially developed
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] by the primary author and applied to two pilot interviews.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] The co-authors then reviewed the codebook and provided
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] suggested revisions, which mainly involved simplifying and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] condensing the number of codes, and adding in demo-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] graphic codes. The primary coder finished coding the re-
