[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] maining interviews, and went through a second round of re-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] views, in which one co-author randomly selected two inter-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] views (one each from the US and UK) to review. On the
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] basis of this review, the primary coder refined the codebook
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] and methodology, after which they ensured that the method-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ology was uniformly applied across interviews, to establish
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ‘internal consistency’ (Guba 1981). The final codebook had
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] 5 main code families, 36 sub-codes and 144 codes.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] Results and Findings
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] AI as the ‘Wild West’ of Medicine
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] The first key finding was that strategies for adoption and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] governance of AI devices varied widely across the 15 insti-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tutions represented in our interview sample. This finding
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] was surprisingly consistent across the US and UK, despite
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] the UK’s relatively more centralized NHS system.
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] UK participants noted that in order to incentivize greater
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] adoption of AI, the government fully funded stroke detec-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] tion AI devices within NHS trusts in England in 2020, and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] later set up an AI Diagnostic Fund (GOV.UK. 2023), which
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] provides funding for NHS trusts to deploy a wide range of
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] AI systems. Despite this centralized funding stream, how-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ever, participants suggested that the way that these devices
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] were adopted and governed depended on the availability of
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] individual hospital resources:
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] “I think the current way we do it is you've got money
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] coming down from above…to support projects and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] then…[it’s] developed locally and you've got very dif-
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] ferent approaches to it depending on resources and
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] need…I worry that…some places are doing it in a way
[2026-04-04 18:23:51] [stdout] that…is slightly dodgy because they just don't
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] have…the infrastructure or the resources to do it well.”
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] (Radiologist, non-AHSC, UK).
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Although US academic medical centers tended to be well-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] resourced, participants still highlighted variance in whether
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] or not a hospital has a governance policy for AI.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “Oh yeah, AI is the Wild West in medicine…So some
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] hospitals may not have any governance at all. We're
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] developing a governance policy, so technically we
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] don't…have one…actively in use right now… same
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] thing goes with other hospitals I've worked at.” (Clini-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] cal Medical Physicist, Academic Medical Centre, US).
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] In addition to differences in resources, participants specu-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] lated about some of the other reasons for this variation
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] across hospitals. One radiologist from a US academic med-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ical center suggested that the ‘slow boil’ nature of AI adop-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tion makes it appear deceptively low risk when compared
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] with previous technologies:
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “AI…has been so insidious that… it's become inte-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] grated…piece by piece… it's a…slow boil…we didn’t
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] expect the radiologist…who's never been trained on a
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] CT [to] say, oh yeah, I know how to use this… [with
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] AI] practices [are]…caught unaware… you realize…
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] we have 5 tools and we're not really tracking quality for
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] any of these.. [and seeing] if this is being used effec-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tively.” (Radiologist, Academic Medical Center, US).
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] In line with this observation, some participants ques-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tioned whether AI should be viewed as a medical device in
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] need of strict guardrails and monitoring, or just ‘another
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] piece of software’ (Clinical Scientist, non-AHSC, UK), or
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ‘software plugin’ (Radiologist, Academic Medical Centre,
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] US). Despite some variance in participant attitudes regard-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ing the level of risk posed by AI systems, and the rigorous-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ness of governance needed to mitigate these risks, partici-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] pants commonly pointed out that AI use generated new con-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] cerns regarding overreliance, bias, performance on local pa-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tient data, lack of AI expertise among deployers/users, lack
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] of explainability, and performance drift over time.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Responsibility ‘Negotiation’ Across Stakeholders
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Across our interviews, we found that although participants
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] commonly believed that the clinician has the ‘final respon-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] sibility’ over AI-related outcomes, in line with previous
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] studies (Jones, Thornton, and Wyatt; Van Cauwenberge et
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] al. 2022), AI deployments had also necessitated the negoti-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ation of new responsibility norms within the hospital.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Participants typically named the responsible person as the
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] one who had ‘signed the report’, ‘acted on the report’, or
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ‘made a decision with the tool’, while in some cases they
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] named a specific clinical stakeholder like the radiologist or
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] clinician. Less commonly, participants referred to hospitals
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] as the main responsible party, or mentioned shared respon-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] sibility with the vendor, while one radiation oncologist
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] stated that no one should be responsible, “if everyone’s done
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] their best and acts in good faith” (Clinical Scientist, non-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] AHSC, UK). Participants who viewed clinicians as having
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ‘final responsibility’ often cited legal liability, while others
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] cited professional norms, duties to patients, or vendors’ un-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] willingness to take on this responsibility. These perspectives
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] suggest the emerging risk of ‘moral crumple zones’, partic-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ularly if clinicians take on responsibility for outcomes for
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] which they lack either knowledge or control (Elish 2019;
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Smith and Fotheringham 2020).
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Even those who were initially confident about clinicians
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] having the ‘final responsibility’, later acknowledged that the
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] answer would be less straightforward if AI was used more
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] autonomously. A few US radiologists said that they would
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] have to look to the automotive industry to understand how
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] this would play out legally. In some cases, when an AI sys-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tem was used for diagnosis by non-radiologists, new respon-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] sibilities could be added to existing roles:
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] 1022
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “We’ve had cases where the AI has said…there’s a
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] hemorrhage here. And it’s been reviewed by a radiolo-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] gist who's said that there isn’t. But the clinician sees the
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] AI results… [and] either acts on that…or they'll ques-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tion the radiologist's opinion…I heard of a case [where]
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] the physician insisted that the radiologist call a neuro-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] radiologist at a different center. And this is in the mid-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] dle of the night to confirm that there was no hemor-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] rhage and so it led to a whole load of extra work” (Ra-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] diologist, AHSC, UK).
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Participants also expressed ambivalence about who
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] should be responsible for evaluating AI system performance
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] over time; a finding that was consistent with a recent study
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] (Chow, Lee, and Wu 2025).
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “So…there's a couple of different routes we could take
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] [for monitoring]…but…it's kind of no point in going
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] too far down the road until someone agrees whose re-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] sponsibility it is...Because if you have hundreds of AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tools…that's a big job...coming into the trust. Should it
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] be a central group? Should it be…each individual de-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] partment that takes responsibility? I don't know the an-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] swer really.” (Clinical Scientist, non-AHSC, UK)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Some participants asserted that it was the responsibility
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] of individual departments to monitor performance, while
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] others suggested that there should be a more centralized
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] body, such as the NHS, or an independent third party, in
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] charge of performance monitoring. A US radiologist men-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tioned that it was the responsibility of their hospital’s AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] governance group to work with different sections to put to-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] gether viable test data prior to deploying the system to a
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] small group of test users (Radiologist, US, Academic Med-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ical Center). Another US radiologist stated that due to a lack
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] of resources, their approach was to trust vendors to report
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] performance, but added that ideally it would be better to
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] have an independent body conducting evaluations (Radiol-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ogist, US, non-Academic Medical Center). These perspec-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tives suggest that performance evaluation is approached
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] very differently based on resources and capacity, and point
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] to potential ‘gaps’ that emerge if no one is ultimately taking
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] on this responsibility.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Designing ‘Bottom-Up’ Governance Approaches
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Across our interviews, we observed that hospital-level gov-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ernance committees tended to be formed through a ‘bottom-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] up’ process driven by motivated clinical staff (who we refer
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] to as governance entrepreneurs). These individuals often
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] wrestled with key questions regarding the appropriate scope,
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] composition, remit, and role for their committee, and high-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] lighted the importance of counteracting perceived inadequa-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] cies in stakeholder engagement, procurement processes,
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] pre-deployment testing, and/or ongoing performance moni-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] toring. Participants who were part of working groups devel-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] oping best practice guidelines within professional societies
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tended to describe a similar “bottom-up” approach.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] While some governance roles were formally included as
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] part of participant job descriptions, many governance func-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tions were undertaken on a completely voluntary basis,
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] sometimes by temporary employees such as medical stu-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] dents and residents. Thus, much like regulatory “policy en-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] trepreneurs” or “political actors who engage in collaborative
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] efforts in and around government to promote policy innova-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tions” (Durant and Diehl 1989), these governance entrepre-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] neurs exhibit a similar “willingness to invest their resources
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] – time, energy, reputation, and sometimes money – in the
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] hope of a future return” (Durant and Diehl 1989). Govern-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ance entrepreneurs in our study referenced “goodwill,” or
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] doing the work “because we think it's the right thing to do,
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] not because there's money attached or any resource” (Clini-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] cal Scientist, UK, non-AHSC).
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Many of the participants pushing for more formalized AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] governance processes within their radiology department
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] were radiation oncologists with scientific backgrounds. For
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] these participants, governance appeared to represent a
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] chance to have a seat at the table, and provide expertise. As
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] one participant noted:
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “You don't tend to get our profession at senior levels
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] and trusts, so they wouldn't even know to come and
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] find us... lots of people I know do complain about being
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] essentially overlooked…when they could help.” (Clin-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ical Scientist, UK, non-AHSC)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] One challenge faced by governance entrepreneurs was
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] determining the scope of governance, given the use of AI for
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] a wide range of different tasks:
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “One thing that concerns me is not being general
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] enough...I've noticed people tend to fixate on things
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] that…impact their day-to-day profession. So like radi-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ologists focus more on CAD AI systems. Physicists
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] might be more focused on…image acquisition...I've
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] identified that there's these sort of niche groups. My
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] bigger concern is policies that can…govern all AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] in…radiology.” (Medical Physicist, Academic Medi-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] cal Centre, US)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Another participant viewed the increasing scope as a nat-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ural response to the more widespread use of AI:
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “[Our committee] started out as AI in radiology and
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] we've transitioned that more to AI in imaging because
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] all of our tools are imaging based. But it is possible that
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] you know that will eventually be rebranded
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] again…eventually it'll be an AI in medicine, as we con-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tinue to change and bring on more applications.” (Ra-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] diologist, Academic Medical Centre, US)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] 1023
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Participants also highlighted the challenge of deciding
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] which stakeholders should be involved in their department’s
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] governance committee. One US radiation oncologist de-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] scribed a committee involving ‘physicians, imaging scien-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tists…nursing staff…representation from IS and IT…and an
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ethicist’ (Radiation Oncologist, US, Academic Medical
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Centre).  Another US radiologist mentioned the involvement
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] of staff with expertise on the ‘clinical side…quality assur-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ance side…information security side…development side’
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] (Radiologist, US, Academic Medical Center). This partici-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] pant also mentioned that their governance committee was
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] modeled off of recommendations made by a paper (Daye et
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] al. 2022) published in a medical journal. A UK radiation on-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] cologist mentioned the inclusion of patients as ‘part of the
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] [governance] panel, and also part of a separate parallel
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] panel’ (Radiation Oncologist, UK, AHSC), while a US ra-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] diation oncologist expressed interest in considering different
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] stakeholders, including the section chief, and ethical/regula-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tory experts, but worried about how ‘efficient the committee
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] would work if we even introduced all these different people’
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] (Medical Physicist, US, Academic Medical Center)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Governance entrepreneurs also deliberated about what in-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] formation their committee should request from clinicians in-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] terested in purchasing a new AI tool. This concern also
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] played a role in participants’ views of their committee as ei-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ther being a ‘gatekeeper’ or merely providing ‘oversight’.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “Our committee is mostly not in the business of…re-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] jecting things typically. Usually the idea is to push back
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] and say this you need to do a better job of documenting
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] this piece or justifying that or thinking about…this...
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] but I think there's…concern that if they're too…force-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] fully saying no …people are gonna find ways to go
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] around it as opposed to…going through it” (Radiation
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Oncologist,
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Academic
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Medical
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Center,
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] US)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Perspectives on the role of the committee differed across
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] hospitals, however. The participant referenced above noted
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] that committees at other hospitals may envision their role
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] differently, with some considering the goal to be to ‘reject
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] things they don’t think will be useful’, and act as a ‘toll
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] booth.’ Echoing this sentiment, one UK radiation oncologist
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] explicitly referred to their committee process as a “gate-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] way…primarily concerned with commercial tools,” (Clini-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] cal Scientist, UK, non-AHSC) and multiple participants
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] (from US Academic Medical Centers) mentioned several
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] rounds of acceptability thresholds that needed to be met for
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] a tool to be deployed.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Governance entrepreneurs also faced challenges integrat-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ing new frameworks within existing policies. In particular,
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] UK-based practitioners discussed challenges with conduct-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ing rigorous due diligence of AI systems, due to existing in-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] formation governance and procurement laws.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “Procurement is very rigid. There's not really a mecha-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] nism for evaluating how well…each individual tool
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] works [on] your own dataset locally. You just have
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] to…ask them for evidence and score it based on
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] that...we're trying to persuade our procurement col-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] leagues…to do something different for AI…I think it's
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] going to be hard…because…the system they use [is
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] the]…legally agreed way to procure things.” (Radiolo-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] gist, UK, non-AHSC)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] The desire to test AI systems on local data before deploy-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ment has led to the design of pilot programs or trial periods,
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] but hospitals diverged in their approach to these as well.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Trial periods could involve deploying the AI system in
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ‘shadow mode’, meaning that the AI system is working in
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] the background and collecting data on performance metrics.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] In some hospitals, these trials were followed by small
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] rollouts and feedback from focus groups. However, several
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] participants mentioned manufacturers’ reluctance to offer
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] trial periods, while some mentioned challenges in determin-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ing how long trial periods should be.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Participants noted that merely testing the AI system be-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] fore deployment does not guarantee stable performance over
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] time. Thus, designing performance monitoring guidelines
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] was also a common challenge expressed by participants.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] One participant highlighted the lack of a ‘gold standard’ for
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] evaluation:
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “Only a handful of places could even attempt being
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] able to really do a rigorous evaluation…and then the
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] question of course becomes who's the gold standard?
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Maybe the experts didn't see anything, but maybe
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] [there are] hidden things that the AI is using to make
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] its determination.” (Radiologist, Academic Medical
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Centre, US)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] In addition to designing new guidelines, governance en-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] trepreneurs also have to navigate challenges in enforcement,
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] particularly when aspects of governance, such as perfor-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] mance monitoring, are devolved to individual departments.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “I think the main risk we face clinically is that so much
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] work goes into navigating the initial governance prob-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] lems [that] post deployment surveillance is…an after-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] thought…they go ok so you want me to do what?...give
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] you… monthly reports…demonstrating the ongoing
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] efficacy or… validity of the model...Whereas…if these
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] were things done by a staff actor, then of course…we
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] would have audit, we would have review...appraisal
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] mechanisms.” (Radiation Oncologist, AHSC, UK)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Finally, some governance entrepreneurs highlighted the
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] need to find funding for their operations. While larger insti-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tutions with resources and buy-in from higher ups did not
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] face this problem, some participants in the UK mentioned
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] applying for short-term grants, through AI-specific fellow-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ships or charitable funding bodies.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] 1024
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Suggested Governance Actions
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Streamlined Guidance for Responsible Adoption
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Participants commonly mentioned that there were too many
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] regulatory and professional bodies involved in setting
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] guidelines for AI.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “I mean, everybody's sort of like the dog in the neigh-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] borhood that pees all over and wants to claim as
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] much…of the neighborhood as his domain as possible.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] So I think there are lots of people that have done lots of
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] things with governance.” (Radiologist, Academic
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Medical Center, US)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “There's almost too many [governing bodies] involved,
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] with competing or overlapping scope and priorities.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] But in terms of...NHS E, NHS digital or all the differ-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ent…colleges and institutions and stuff…and MHRA
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] and the government…” (Clinical Scientist, UK, non-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] AHSC)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] One US radiation oncologist expressed concerns around
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] the ‘confusion’ generated if people are unsure which gov-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ernance guidelines to use (Medical Physicist, US, Academic
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Medical Center), while another UK radiologist called on the
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] NHS to have one dedicated body focused on ensuring AI is
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] deployed safely NHS-wide (Radiologist, UK, non-AHSC).
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Education/Training Across Hospital Staff
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Participants commonly noted the importance of better edu-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] cation and training for clinicians/staff procuring and using
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] AI systems. They highlighted that education could ensure
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] that clinicians are not misled by vendor marketing.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “When I've been on a call with a vendor, they pushed
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] heavily that their tool was CE marked… a radiologist
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] who I spoke to…when I said… just because it's CE
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] marked doesn't mean it works [on your hospital’s data].
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] [They were] like, well, I thought that is what that
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] meant. And [they’ve] deployed some AI tools in [their]
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] trust.” (Clinical Scientist, UK, non-AHSC)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Participants also suggested that education was needed to
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] prevent users from blindly relying on AI systems. A US-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] based researcher likened the need for education to the need
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] to pass a driving test (Researcher, US, AHSC), while a US
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] radiologist suggested that AI should be treated as a core
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] competency within radiology education, and included on
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] board exams (Radiologist, US, AHSC). Participants differed
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] in their assessment of who should be responsible for educa-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tion, with some mentioning hospitals themselves, others
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] mentioning professional societies, and still others suggest-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ing the need for government involvement.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Knowledge Sharing
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Participants often suggested that better knowledge sharing
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] was needed across institutions.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] “There's really not a Consumer Reports that exists right
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] now for AI. There's…AI vendors…claiming accuracy
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] out in the field of a certain amount…It's incredible that
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] you end up purchasing something…and trust without
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] any real data on its performance…we're going
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] to…[need] a relatively neutral repository of real data
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] that people have collected on different algorithms.”
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] (Radiologist, Academic Medical Center, US)
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Another US radiologist called for ‘public summaries’ of
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] performance, while some UK participants lamented the lack
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] of communication across different NHS trusts. In both the
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] US and UK, liability concerns and professional reputation
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] were raised as potential barriers to sharing this information.
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Stakeholder Engagement
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Participants highlighted the need for engaging stakeholders
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] at every stage of AI deployment. A UK radiologist sug-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] gested that the lack of stakeholder engagement before intro-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] ducing a stroke detection algorithm had made practitioners
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] biassed against using it, with some even turning the system
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] off (Radiologist, UK, AHSC). A few radiation oncologists
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] (in both the US and UK) emphasized their scientific exper-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] tise—adding that if they were expected to give advice on
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] quality assurance, it was only fair if they were involved with
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] procurement as well. A UK radiation oncologist mentioned
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] that accreditations might be helpful to ensure that there are
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] designated AI experts at each NHS trust responsible for
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] overseeing AI deployments (Clinical Scientist, UK, non-
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] AHSC).
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Other Participant Recommendations
[2026-04-04 18:23:52] [stdout] Participants occasionally mentioned that clinical trials or
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] prospective studies should be conducted for AI devices. One
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] participant suggested that companies should subsidize trials,
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] citing the example of clinical trials for drugs (Clinical Sci-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] entist, UK, non-AHSC). Less commonly, participants sug-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] gested that patients should be informed if AI is being used
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] in their care, through obtaining explicit consent (Radiolo-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] gist, UK, non-AHSC), or being informed by discharge sum-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] mary (Medical Physicist, US, Academic Medical Center). A
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] few UK-specific suggestions were also raised by radiation
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] oncologists: one participant mentioned the need for over-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] hauling information governance, while another participant
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] highlighted the need for new AI-specific NHS procurement
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] guidelines (Clinical Scientist, UK, non-AHSC).
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Discussion
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Our interview findings underscore clear challenges emerg-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ing in responsibility attribution and governance of AI in ra-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] diology. Participants highlighted the importance of re-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] sources and expertise in determining the nature of both AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] 1025
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] adoption and governance, echoing previous studies (Baten
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] 2024; Raimo et al. 2023; Zhang et al. 2013; Chow, Lee, and
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Wu 2025 ). However, a newer insight was participants’ re-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] flections on how the perception of AI as ‘just another piece
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] of software’ versus a formal medical device may be impact-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ing the way that AI is adopted and governed as well.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Although participants generally viewed clinicians as hav-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ing “final responsibility” over AI-related outcomes, echoing
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] previous findings (Jones, Thornton, and Wyatt; Van
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Cauwenberge et al. 2022), participants noted that increas-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ingly autonomous deployments of AI might challenge this
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] existing framework, especially if errors were due to a lack
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] of due diligence by commercial vendors. Some highlighted
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] already shifting responsibility norms in instances where AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] had been used to deal with worker shortages after hours. At
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] the same time, participants commonly noted that staff in ra-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] diology departments were not adequately trained to use AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] systems. These findings suggest that the ‘moral crumple
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] zone’ presents as a real risk for healthcare practitioners.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] When it comes to governance, it is unclear who should be
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] responsible for the various different quality control
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] measures necessitated by AI systems, including pre-deploy-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ment testing and post-deployment monitoring. This lack of
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] clarity stems not only from the nascent stage of literature
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] and best practices on AI evaluations, but also the lack of ca-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] pacity for most health systems to take on such a task. The
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] most rigorous AI governance committees tended to take on
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] this role, but other committees relied on individual ‘clinical
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] champions’ or those interested in purchasing the AI system,
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] to monitor performance and report back to the committee.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] More centralized approaches to performance monitoring,
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] such as an NHS-wide initiative, or third-party evaluations
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] were also suggested. It is possible that such centralized ap-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] proaches might even be more effective at catching popula-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tion-wide impacts of these systems, but it is unclear if a cen-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tralized body will take on this responsibility. Here, a tension
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] emerges between top-down and bottom-up approaches to
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] governance.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Similarly, the profession also faces challenges in deciding
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] who should be responsible for issuing guidelines and shar-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ing best practices for AI. Participants highlighted concerns
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] about too many professional and regulatory bodies being in-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] volved in AI (‘many hands’), sometimes having competing
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] priorities/goals. To that end, participants commonly men-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tioned a desire for better coordination and more streamlined
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] guidelines. When conducting further research, we came
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] across one cross-society statement from US professional so-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] cieties on AI (Brady et al. 2024). Whether or not participants
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] were aware of this statement, it appeared as though they
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] were looking for stronger, implementable guidelines. How-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ever, participants also noted that the liability norms in med-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] icine could be a barrier to knowledge sharing and strong
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ‘guidelines’, as individuals and institutions typically wait to
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] establish a strong evidence base before putting out infor-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] mation. But establishing this evidence base for AI is tricky,
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] as adoption is happening much quicker than people can
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] study its effects, and in countries like the UK, information
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] governance often prevents research groups from being able
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] to access data for years at a time, slowing down the process
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] of evaluation. Moreover, the performance of AI systems can
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] be very dependent on characteristics of particular patient
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] populations, making it that much more challenging to pro-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] vide ‘general’ recommendations.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Motivated groups of individuals have stepped into this
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] context to design novel AI-specific policies and approaches
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] at their individual institutions. These ‘governance entrepre-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] neurs’ commit resources to developing new governance in-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] terventions that they believe will pay off in the long run.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] However, like entrepreneurs in other contexts, they can only
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] be successful if they have access to adequate resources, such
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] as capital and expert input. Our findings suggest that lower
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] resource hospitals tend to lack the resources to adequately
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] test and monitor AI system performance. Therefore, some
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] hospitals are relying on temporary or voluntary employees,
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] such as medical residents, for testing and validation pur-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] poses. Yet this does not offer a sustainable path for ensuring
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] the safety of AI systems over time. Thus, the current manner
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] of AI deployment risks entrenching existing inequalities
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] across health systems.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Importantly, the governance entrepreneurs we inter-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] viewed differ from entrepreneurs in other fields as they con-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tinue to operate within deeply hierarchical organizations.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Thus, they must navigate power relations, justify their role,
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] and rely on buy-in from higher ups on the importance of AI-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] specific governance. Many participants who had pushed for
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] stronger AI governance were radiation oncologists. Some of
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] them mentioned that despite their scientific expertise, and
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] responsibility for quality assurance, they were sometimes
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] overlooked when AI systems were deployed at their hospi-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tal. The power held by an AI governance committee is also
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] highly organizationally specific, with some having strict en-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] forcement power and others merely guiding or overseeing
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] AI deployments. Additionally, the medical profession’s in-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tentionally siloed, specialty-driven approach appears to be
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] at-odds with increasingly wide-ranging use of AI across dif-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ferent contexts. This creates new challenges in understand-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ing whose expertise should be included when overseeing AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] deployments, and how wide the scope of governance com-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] mittees should be.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] The governance solutions suggested by participants re-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] quire resources, navigating political tensions, and breaking
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] down legal and structural barriers to collaboration. Devel-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] oping better AI training for staff would require resources to
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] be invested either at the individual hospital-level, or on a
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] higher level, by institutions involved in setting medical
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] school curricula. Incentivizing individual hospitals to be
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] 1026
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] more transparent about AI use and performance would re-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] quire resources for monitoring and publishing this infor-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] mation, and also potentially require addressing liability is-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] sues. Coordination across individual hospitals and profes-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] sional bodies could require a restructuring of the specialty-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] driven approach to medical knowledge sharing, and buy-in
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] from professional and regulatory bodies with complex po-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] litical entanglements. Participants’ suggestions of more
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] streamlined ‘general’ guidance, while also calling for better
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] local governance infrastructure, also present potential ten-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] sions between top-down and bottom-up approaches to gov-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ernance. General guidelines might be less desired if they are
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] made mandatory and prevent local hospitals from account-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ing for their own unique patient populations. On the other
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] hand, leaving governance completely up to individual hos-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] pitals could create equity issues.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Policy interventions could be pursued by governing bod-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ies at various levels. Governments could create opportuni-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ties for collaboration and streamlining of AI-related guid-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ance. Grants could be made available for hospitals lacking
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] the resources to set up their own governance committees.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Hospitals could also be encouraged to consider whether they
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] have the capacity for conducting due diligence prior to im-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] plementing AI solutions. Independent, umbrella organiza-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tions could be created to enable institutions to share infor-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] mation, and research funding could be made available for
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] generating real-world evidence on AI deployments. Central-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ized approaches to performance monitoring could also be
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] pursued, and potentially subsidized by commercial vendors.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] The need for resources poses a real challenge to imple-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] menting the interventions suggested above. Investing in AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] governance would make AI implementation more expen-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] sive, and probably be seen as counterintuitive to the ‘effi-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ciency’ goals that hospital systems hope that AI will help
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] them achieve. However, poorly implemented AI systems
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] run the risk of either being shut off by clinicians, making the
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] investment a waste, or threatening the well-being of patients
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] and clinicians alike. While some might argue that the even-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tual efficiency gains realized by AI will pay for initial in-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] vestments, this is not yet clear. As some industry and regu-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] latory participants pointed out, it is hard to place a price on
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] the savings that AI will bring in the future.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] In future work, it would be interesting to explore the prac-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tical viability of these different interventions. Placing these
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] recommendations within the broader context of current AI-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] related policy instruments, like healthcare AI regulatory
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] sandboxes (Qiu et al. 2025), could also enable more reflec-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tion on the relationship between bottom-up and top-down
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] approaches. With a greater sample size of participants
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] across different countries, more explicitly comparative anal-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ysis could be done across jurisdictions. Researchers could
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] also extend this work to other medical specialty areas, be-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] yond radiology, and other domains, like government AI
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] adoption, to see if similar trends emerge.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Limitations
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Our study presents the following limitations. First, our lack
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] of access to healthcare professionals from lower-resource
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] hospitals limits our equity-related analysis to participant
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] perspectives that were derived from anecdotal conversations
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] with other colleagues. Second, our lack of inclusion of IT
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] professionals makes it possible that we missed context re-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] garding the role of hospital-level infrastructure challenges
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] in AI adoption and governance. Additionally, being a single-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] coded study, our interpretation of the results may contain
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] biases, although these were mitigated through regular peer
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] debriefing. Finally, although our sample size of 22 partici-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] pants reached saturation, given the qualitative nature of this
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] study, the conclusions presented are not necessarily gener-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] alizable.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] Conclusion
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] In this paper, we explore the emergence of ‘bottom-up’ ap-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] proaches to AI governance in radiology departments in the
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] US and UK. In interviewing 22 experts in clinical adoption
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] and governance of AI in radiology, we survey the current
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] state of AI governance in hospitals. The findings of this
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] study highlight novel challenges to responsibility and gov-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ernance generated by AI, including the assignation of re-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] sponsibility for new governance functions like post-deploy-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ment monitoring, and re-negotiation of responsibility norms
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] when AI is deployed more autonomously. Additionally, dif-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] fering views on which governance functions should be con-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ducted locally versus centrally indicate an underlying ten-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] sion between bottom-up and top-down approaches. In our
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] in-depth examination of committees of ‘governance entre-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] preneurs’ within different hospitals, we find great variation
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] in the scope, composition, remit, and role of these commit-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tees, and note challenges faced in navigating power relations
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] and resource constraints within hierarchical organizations.
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] In particular, we note that the medical profession’s spe-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] cialty-driven approach appears increasingly at-odds with the
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] wide-ranging use of AI across different contexts in the hos-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] pital, creating new challenges in understanding whose ex-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] pertise should be included when overseeing AI deploy-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] ments. While professional societies and governing bodies
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] have released guidelines to help hospitals govern AI, the
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] overwhelming number of competing recommendations has
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] made them difficult to implement. We conclude with some
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] recommended interventions to cope with these challenges,
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] including investing resources into staff training and local
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] governance, and improving coordination across siloed insti-
[2026-04-04 18:23:53] [stdout] tutions.
