[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] 
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout]         # PAPER BODY TEXT:
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout]         ---
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout]         Introduction
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] “I still expect that it will be some change required to the
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] social contract given how powerful we expect this
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] technology to be...the whole structure of society itself will be
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] up for some degree of debate and reconfiguration”
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] – Sam Altman
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Artificial intelligence (AI) is increasingly embedded across
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] public systems of governance, informing decisions related
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] to welfare entitlements, policing, employment, and
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] administrative coordination. Often developed by private
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Copyright © 2025, Association for the Advancement of Artificial
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Intelligence (www.aaai.org). All rights reserved.
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] companies and deployed with limited transparency or
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] oversight, these systems raise fundamental questions about
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] how authority is exercised and legitimated within
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] democratic polities. Algorithmic systems now serve as
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] structural mediators between the citizen and the state,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] shaping entitlements, civil freedoms, and opportunities for
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] public participation (Crawford 2021; Eubanks 2018;
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Pasquale 2015). Certain structural features of AI and its
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] governance make these legitimacy questions especially
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] acute: their tendency to produce collective, diffuse harms
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] that do not map neatly onto individual or product liability
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] frameworks; responsibility gaps that emerge from opaque
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] design and decision-making processes; and the mismatch
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] between AI’s well-established global reach and the
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] territorially bounded authority of most governing bodies.
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] These normative and structural challenges urge an
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] assessment of the legitimacy of modern AI governance,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] particularly when those impacted possess little ability to
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] comprehend, challenge, or assent to their deployment
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] (Ananny and Crawford 2018; Mittelstadt 2019; Wagner
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] 2016).
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Social contract theory provides a foundational framework
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] for evaluating the legitimacy of political authority. The
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] tradition, spanning from classical philosophers like Hobbes,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Locke, and Rousseau to contemporary theorists such as
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Rawls and Nozick, posits that governance is legitimate
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] when institutions are based on consent, provide public
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] goods, and safeguard liberty and fairness (Freeman 2007;
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Gaus 2010). Despite their divergent perspectives on
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] sovereignty, justice, and rights, they largely converge on the
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] idea that authority requires more than coercion or legal
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] enforcement; rather, it must be justified to those who are
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] subject to it. In the context of algorithmic governance, where
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] individuals frequently lack participation opportunities,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] confront automated decisions impacting fundamental rights,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] and encounter systems devoid of meaningful contestation
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] mechanisms, this tradition offers a powerful conceptual lens
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] to assess the ethical implications of such emerging
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] institutional arrangements (Beetham 2013; Tyler 2006).
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Proceedings of the Eighth AAAI/ACM Conference on AI, Ethics, and Society (AIES 2025)
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] 615
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] While scholarship has explored AI through contractarian
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] ideas, including concepts such as the “algorithmic social
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] contract” (Rahwan 2018), “machine justice” (Gabriel 2022),
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] and AI legitimacy within transnational regimes (Erman and
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Furendal 2024), most draw on a single philosophical
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] tradition, often Rawlsian or constructivist. In contrast, the
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] internal diversity of the social contract tradition—
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] encompassing absolutist, republican, liberal, and libertarian
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] strands—has not been applied in a systematic manner to
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] assess AI’s implications for the social contract. As a result,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] we lack a clear and comprehensive picture of how
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] contemporary AI and its governance measure up to the
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] political legitimacy standards articulated by different
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] theories. Moreover, there is little understanding of how
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] effectively these traditions can account for AI’s structural
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] features, or whether their underlying assumptions and
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] proposals remain adequate in the algorithmic era.
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] This paper addresses these gaps by conducting a
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] comparative analysis, applying five key social contract
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] theories—Hobbes, Locke, Rousseau, Rawls, and Nozick.
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] These canonical theorists were selected because their
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] approaches represent distinct philosophical models:
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] sovereign absolutism, natural-rights liberalism, civic
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] republicanism, egalitarian constructivism, and libertarian
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] minimalism, respectively (Freeman 2007; Gaus 2010). Each
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] provides a different account of legitimate authority, and
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] each has had substantial influence on liberal-democratic
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] theory and contemporary governance. The analysis focuses
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] on how each theorist defines two core mechanisms of
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] political authority: subjective legitimacy and consent,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] dimensions that constitute key normative foundations of
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] democratic governance (Habermas 2015), and that are under
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] strain in the contemporary AI-mediated world.
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Subjective legitimacy refers to a citizen’s belief that a
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] system of authority is justified, and is composed of
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] perceptions
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] surrounding
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] fairness,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] recognition,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] and
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] accountability.
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] It
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] reflects
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] the
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] alignment
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] between
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] institutional design and public moral standards (Beetham
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] 2013; Tyler 2006). In the context of AI governance, such
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] legitimacy is arguably weakened by opacity, limited public
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] participation, and the difficulty of attributing responsibility
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] for decisions, among other factors.
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Consent, especially in its hypothetical forms, often
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] operates as a moral test: would reasonable individuals,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] under impartial conditions, agree to the institutional rules
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] that govern them (Habermas 2015; Rawls 1971)? Under
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] current AI regimes, individuals typically do not grant
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] explicit consent to data-driven policy decisions and rarely
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] encounter mechanisms that meet the standards of
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] democratic justification (Eubanks 2018; Srinivasan and
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Ghosh 2023), such as sufficient knowledge, meaningful
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] access, and genuine prospects for contestation or
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] remediation (Wagner 2016; Ananny and Crawford 2018;
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] Mittelstadt 2019).
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] The comparative analysis in this study utilizes these two
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] analytic axes, reviewing three forms of legitimacy—
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] procedural, moral-substantive and recognitional, and three
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] notions of consent—explicit, tacit, and hypothetical. These
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] categories, grounded in established political theory
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] scholarship (Gaus 2010; Riley 2013), serve as useful
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] benchmarks for evaluating contemporary AI and its
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] governance. The comparative method employed here allows
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] for a systematic and transparent comparison of how each
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] thinker justifies authority, defines the grounds of agreement,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] and sets the conditions for legitimate governance. The
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] analysis reveals that algorithmic systems challenge these
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] standards in distinct ways across theoretical models,
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] exposing the points at which canonical requirements for
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] legitimacy and consent are least compatible with current AI
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] practices.
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] By mapping these requirements against the operational
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] realities of AI governance, the study ultimately identifies a
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] legitimacy gap that spans all traditions. While each theory
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] sets its own justificatory thresholds, all five reveal
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] incompatibilities with the current approach to AI in public
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] governance. In some traditions, this misalignment concerns
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] the absence of voluntary agreement; in others, the lack of
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] moral justification or collective authorship. As such, this
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] gap cannot be addressed through modest refinements to
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] procedural compliance alone; instead, it reflects a deeper
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] structural misalignment between technological authority
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] and the normative conditions for political legitimacy that
[2026-04-04 18:25:57] [stdout] may urge a reformation of the social contract. In response,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] the study draws on insights from all five theories and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] proposes normative strategies to better calibrate legitimacy
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] under
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] AI
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] governance.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] These
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] include
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] embedding
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] participatory
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] mechanisms,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] ensuring
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] institutional
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] transparency, and strengthening democratic oversight in
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] ways that better reflect pluralistic perspectives (Helbing et
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] al. 2019).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] This study contributes to theoretical and practical debates.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Theoretically, it advances an analytic framework that
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] differentiates types of legitimacy and consent across five
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] major contractarian scholars, revealing points of divergence
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] and convergence raised by modern conditions and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] underexamined in the literature. Practically, it develops
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] evaluative standards and normative insights that can guide
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] the institutional design and democratic oversight of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] algorithmic systems. Two further notes are in order. First,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] while the analysis centers on certain canonical theories,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] critical traditions, including feminist and postcolonial
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] critiques of the social contract, may further illuminate or
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] challenge the limits of the canonical frameworks used here
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] (Mills 2019; Okin 1989). Second, AI systems are not treated
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] as moral agents themselves in our analysis, but rather
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] understood as structural mediators of political power. Future
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] work may benefit from conceptualizing AI systems as actors
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] in the social contract.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] The remainder of the paper proceeds as follows. It begins
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] with a brief justification of the relevance of social contract
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] theory for AI governance, and an introduction to the study’s
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] analytical focus on legitimacy and consent. This is followed
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] 616
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] by a detailed review of how the canonical philosophers
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] conceptualized the three notions of legitimacy and three
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] notions of consent. Building on this comparison, the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] analysis then applies these categories to assess how
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] structural features of AI interact with and ultimately strain
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] various contractarian standards. The discussion then
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] advances a hybrid normative model that incorporates the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] strengths of multiple traditions while addressing their
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] weaknesses, offering concrete yet adaptable strategies for
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] institutional design, transparency, and accountability in
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] algorithmic systems. The paper concludes by reflecting on
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] its theoretical and practical contributions, noting its
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] limitations, and outlining future research directions at the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] intersection of political theory and the governance of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] emerging technologies, towards the preservation (or
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] reconfiguration) of the social contract.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Why Social Contract Theory for
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] AI Governance?
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Numerous philosophical and ethical lenses have been
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] applied to make sense of AI’s implications, including
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] applied, systematic/normative, and metaethical approaches.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Yet this study’s interest in social contract theory is
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] motivated by its normative focus on the legitimacy of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] institutional authority. Contractarian theory is well-
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] positioned to make sense of these issues which are
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] underexamined compared to more practical, day-to-day
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] issues raised regularly in applied ethics debates (e.g.,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] surrounding privacy or algorithmic bias in a certain context).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] For instance, while consequentialist ethics evaluates
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] authority by outcome utility and virtue ethics emphasizes
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] individual moral cultivation (Nussbaum 2011), social
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] contract theory offers a distinct advantage in addressing
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] AI’s governance dilemmas: it evaluates whether the rules
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] structuring authority are morally justified.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] This emphasis is especially relevant for automated
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] decision-making systems, where rule-based authority is
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] often exercised without transparent deliberation or
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] interpersonal accountability. As Pettit (2012) urges,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] legitimacy requires more than procedural regularity; it
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] demands that institutional actions can be justified to those
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] subject to them. In algorithmic environments, however,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] decisions often arise from opaque optimization or private
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] datasets, placing them beyond the justificatory reach of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] affected citizens. Most individuals lack both epistemic
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] access and procedural standing in AI-driven infrastructures,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] rendering
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] conventional
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] accountability
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] mechanisms
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] ineffective (Srinivasan and Ghosh 2023). For example,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] algorithmic immigration screening tools have denied entry
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] to applicants based on opaque risk models, without offering
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] those affected a meaningful opportunity to understand or
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] contest the decision (Molnar and Gill 2018).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Given such challenges, social contract theory offers a
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] framework not only for asking whether power is effectively
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] exercised, but whether it should be exercised in the first
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] place. Its principles of mutual justification, rational
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] agreement, and reciprocal duty make it especially relevant
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] for examining AI systems that increasingly make policy-
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] relevant determinations without clear channels for
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] democratic validation or redress and for public governance
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] of AI broadly, including within the private sector.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Core Dimensions: Legitimacy and Consent
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Within the social contract tradition, two justificatory
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] mechanisms are especially central to establishing (and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] assessing) the moral authority of political institutions:
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] subjective legitimacy and consent. These mechanisms form
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] the normative foundation for claims to political obligation
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] in liberal-democratic theory (Habermas 2015).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Subjective
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] legitimacy
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] concerns
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] normative
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] justification of authority—whether it is rightfully exercised
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] and recognized by those subject to it (Beetham 2013;
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Buchanan 2002). Political theory commonly distinguishes
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] three
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] forms:
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] procedural,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] moral-substantive,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] recognitional legitimacy (Gaus 2010; Riley 2013). In other
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] words, legitimacy holds a tripartite structure: legality
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] (conformity with rules), shared belief in legitimacy
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] (normative endorsement), and consent (expressed or
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] implied). Empirical studies show that compliance is
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] sustained when citizens perceive institutions as procedurally
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] fair and morally grounded (Tyler 2006).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Consent operates as a moral filter on the use of power: are
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] the governed in a position to reasonably accept the rules that
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] bind them? Classical forms of consent include explicit
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] contracting (Hobbes), tacit obedience (Locke), and active
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] participation (Rousseau), while contemporary theory favors
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] hypothetical consent (Rawls).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] In AI-governed contexts, both mechanisms face
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] challenges. Decisions and institutional designs are often
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] opaque, unaccountable, and imposed without meaningful
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] deliberation. Consent in digital contexts is equally lacking,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] often defaulting into passive data extraction advanced by
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] platform logic, lacking the reflective endorsement
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] envisioned by democratic theory. These developments raise
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] pressing questions: Can AI systems meet the standards of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] political authority? If not, which dimensions of traditional
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] legitimacy are violated, and how might they be restored?
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Divergent Traditions of Legitimacy and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Consent in Classical Social Contract Theories
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Legitimacy Dimensions
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Procedural Legitimacy refers to the extent to which
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] authority is grounded in adherence to formally established
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] rules, institutional roles, and decision-making procedures.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] In Hobbes’s framework, procedural legitimacy is tied to the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] 617
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] sovereign’s ability to enforce laws and maintain order. In
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Leviathan (1651), Hobbes declares, “covenants, without the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] sword, are but words and of no strength” (ch. XVII),
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] indicating that legitimacy stems from the sovereign’s
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] effective capacity to command rather than from public
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] recognition or moral agreement. As Skinner (2008) observes,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Hobbes seeks to relocate all notions of obligation within the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] framework of law as laid down by sovereign power. This
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] model leaves little space for procedural fairness beyond
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] compliance with enacted rules, strongly prioritizing stability
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] over participatory mechanisms.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] In Locke’s account, procedural legitimacy also depends
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] on rule conformity but is conditional upon the protection of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] natural rights. Legislative authority must be exercised “by
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] promulgated standing laws” and “not by extemporary
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] decrees” ( Second Treatise , §124). Laws must be general,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] known, and prospective to be legitimate, embedding
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] procedural requirements within a broader moral framework.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Tuckness (2002) notes that such conditionality constrains
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] arbitrary state action and offers safeguards absent in
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Hobbesian absolutism, linking procedural formality to the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] moral purpose of protecting liberty and property.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Rousseau integrates procedural legitimacy through the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] enactment of laws that reflect the general will, requiring that
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] “the people, being subject to the laws, ought to be their
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] author” ( Social Contract , Book II). This embeds procedure
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] within participatory self-legislation. Yet it remains
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] vulnerable to the critique that large or technologically
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] mediated societies may lack mechanisms to ensure that
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] formal legislative processes truly track the general will
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] (Berlin 2014; Eubanks 2018; Srinivasan and Ghosh 2023).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Rawls reframes procedural legitimacy through the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] concept of “pure procedural justice,” where fairness in
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] decision-making ensures the justice of outcomes only if
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] background conditions are just (Rawls 1971). This vision
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] presupposes equality of opportunity and impartiality,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] conditions often absent in algorithmic governance, where
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] opaque systems can perpetuate structural disadvantage
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] (Mills 2019). Algorithmic credit scoring, for example, can
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] disproportionately
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] lower
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] ratings
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] for
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] historically
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] disadvantaged groups, thereby undermining fair equality of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] opportunity even if the procedure is technically consistent.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Nozick gives procedural legitimacy minimal scope
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] beyond its role in enforcing voluntary agreements. In
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Anarchy, State, and Utopia (1974), legitimacy is satisfied if
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] transactions respect historical entitlements, regardless of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] distributive outcomes. This narrow proceduralism is ill-
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] suited for AI governance contexts in which harms emerge
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] from structural features, such as pervasive data aggregation,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] occurring without meaningful individual transactions much
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] less explicit agreement. Data brokerage ecosystems, which
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] aggregate personal information without explicit user
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] engagement, would likely fall outside Nozick’s procedural
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] concern, even when they lead to large-scale profiling.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Moral-Substantive Legitimacy refers to the extent to which
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] authority is justified by its adherence to ethical standards
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] such as fairness, justice, rights protection, or the promotion
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] of the common good, rather than by procedural compliance
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] alone (Beetham 2013). In Hobbes’s framework, moral-
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] substantive considerations are secondary to stability and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] order. For Hobbes, the sovereign’s role is not to realize
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] distributive justice but to maintain peace, since “where no
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] common power, there is no law; where no law, no injustice”
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] ( Leviathan , ch. XIII). This places Hobbesian legitimacy
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] largely outside moral-substantive tests in the modern
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] democratic sense, as the sovereign’s actions are evaluated in
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] minimalistic terms of preventing societal collapse, not
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] aligning with shared ethical norms (Kavka 2021).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Locke, by contrast, embeds moral-substantive legitimacy
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] explicitly in the preservation of natural rights, including life,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] liberty, and property, as the central end of political society.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Authority becomes illegitimate when it fails to protect these
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] rights, even if procedural norms are followed. In Locke’s
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Second Treatise (§222), he argues that when legislators
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] violate natural rights, they “put themselves into a state of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] war with the people,” thus forfeiting legitimacy (Simmons
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] 2000). However, Locke’s framework assumes a clear and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] stable definition of natural rights, which can be contested or
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] selectively interpreted in pluralistic, technologically
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] mediated societies, limiting its applicability and explanatory
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] power in complex governance environments.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Rousseau’s moral-substantive legitimacy derives from
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] alignment with the general will, understood as the collective
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] moral orientation toward the common good. Laws are
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] legitimate when they embody this will, which Rousseau
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] distinguishes from the mere aggregation of private interests
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] ( Social Contract , Book II). In this view, legitimacy is lost
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] when laws privilege sectional interests over the common
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] good. However, the ambiguity of the general will creates
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] risks of coercion, where dissent may be suppressed under
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] the pretext of pursuing collective morality (Berlin 2014).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Rawls defines moral-substantive legitimacy through the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] two principles of justice articulated in the original position
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] (described later): the equal basic liberties principle and the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] difference principle. Legitimacy depends on whether
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] institutions respect these principles and maintain fair
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] equality of opportunity (Rawls 1971). Rawls explicitly links
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] legitimacy to distributive fairness, arguing that departures
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] from just arrangements require unanimous consent of the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] disadvantaged parties. However, Rawls’s framework,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] grounded in ideal theory, has difficulty engaging with
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] entrenched injustices and the systemic biases of real
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] institutions, which are amplified and complicated in opaque
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] AI-mediated contexts.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Nozick rejects patterned distributive principles as a basis
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] for legitimacy, grounding moral-substantive authority in
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] historical entitlement and the justice of acquisition and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] 618
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] transfer. If holdings arise from just processes, the resulting
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] distribution is legitimate regardless of inequality (Nozick
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] 1974). While this view offers a clear standard for evaluating
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] coercion, it sidelines questions of systemic fairness and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] collective welfare, rendering it poorly equipped to assess
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] legitimacy in AI governance contexts where benefits and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] burdens are distributed through opaque, non-consensual
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] systems that shape structural opportunities (O’Neil 2017).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Recognitional Legitimacy concerns whether authority is
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] affirmed and accepted by those subject to it, not only in
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] terms of compliance, but also with respect to moral and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] symbolic acknowledgement of its right to govern. It reflects
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] the degree to which citizens perceive institutions as
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] representing their values, identity, and political community.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] In Hobbes’s model, recognitional legitimacy plays a
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] minimal role. Because authority derives from the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] sovereign’s capacity to enforce peace, Hobbes sees no
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] requirement for citizens to identify with or morally endorse
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] the sovereign’s decisions. As he states in Leviathan, “the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] obligation of subjects to the sovereign lasts as long, and no
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] longer, than the power lasteth” (ch. XXI). Skinner (2008)
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] emphasizes that Hobbes deliberately sidelines mutual
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] recognition in favor of a security-based compact, leaving
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] little scope for or interest in evaluating governance through
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] shared symbolic commitment.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Locke’s theory, by contrast, treats recognitional
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] legitimacy as integral to sustaining political society.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Because authority rests on consent and trust, citizens must
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] continue to view the government as a rightful trustee of their
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] rights. The withdrawal of this recognition, when rulers
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] “endeavor to take away and destroy the property of the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] people” ( Second Treatise , §222), justifies the dissolution of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] government. Locke’s emphasis on trust implies that
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] recognitional legitimacy is fragile in contexts of systemic
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] opacity or unaccountable decision-making (Tuckness 2009),
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] both of which are endemic to AI governance.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] For Rousseau, recognitional legitimacy is foundational:
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] citizens must see themselves as both authors and subjects of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] the laws. This civic identity is what turns obedience into
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] self-rule. In Social Contract (Book II), Rousseau insists that
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] laws are legitimate only when they arise from collective
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] authorship expressing the general will. However, this model
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] assumes a high degree of civic unity and participation,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] which may be infeasible in large-scale, technologically
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] mediated polities where algorithmic decision-making is
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] removed from public deliberation (Pateman 2015).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Rawls incorporates recognitional legitimacy through the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] idea of public reason: institutions are legitimate when their
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] exercise of political power can be justified to all citizens as
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] free and equal, using reasons they can reasonably accept
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] (Rawls 1993). This requirement entails that legitimacy is
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] sustained not merely through just outcomes but also through
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] ongoing mutual recognition of shared political membership.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Yet as Habermas (2015) points out, this standard
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] presupposes
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] transparent
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] deliberation
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] accessible
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] justificatory processes, both of which are often disrupted by
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] AI’s opaque logic and common conditions of private control.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Nozick assigns minimal importance to recognitional
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] legitimacy, as his framework does not require citizens to
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] identify with the state or its principles beyond refraining
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] from coercion. Legitimacy, in his account, does not depend
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] on mutual recognition but on the state’s non-violation of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] individual rights (Nozick 1974). This leaves little normative
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] space for addressing legitimacy crises that stem from public
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] alienation or distrust, such as issues that are central to
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] debates over AI governance in public administration
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] (Srinivasan and Ghosh 2023).
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Consent Dimensions
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Explicit Consent refers to a clear, deliberate, and
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] documented agreement by individuals to submit to political
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] authority or specific rules. In social contract theory, it
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] represents the most unambiguous form of legitimating
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] assent, though its feasibility and prevalence have been
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] widely debated (Simmons 2014). Hobbes frames the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] commonwealth’s founding as a collective covenant where
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] each person authorizes the sovereign: “I authorize and give
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] up my right of governing myself, to this man, or to this
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] assembly of men” ( Leviathan, ch. XVII). This act is explicit
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] in the initial contract, but thereafter, continued legitimacy
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] does not depend on ongoing consent—only on the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] sovereign’s capacity to provide security. Hobbes treats
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] explicit consent as a one-time founding event (Hampton
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] 1986), which poses a challenge for algorithmic governance
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] that evolves over time without renewed public endorsement.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Locke assigns greater importance to explicit consent,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] particularly in situations where individuals voluntarily join
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] a political society. In Second Treatise (§119), he writes, “no
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] one can be subjected to the political power of another,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] without his own consent.” This form of consent is rare in
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] practice, as Locke acknowledges, but it functions as the
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] clearest form of legitimate authority. For AI governance,
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] explicit consent might parallel formal opt-in mechanisms
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] for algorithmic decision-making. However, real-world AI
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] deployments rarely allow citizens to grant or withhold
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] consent in this clear form, undermining the Lockean ideal.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Rousseau’s conception of explicit consent is bound up
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] with active participation in lawmaking. For him, each
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] citizen’s vote on legislation constitutes an explicit act of
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] consent to the general will ( Social Contract , Book II). While
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] this provides a robust participatory foundation, scholars
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] have pointed out that modern governance rarely affords
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] citizens direct legislative input (Berlin 2014; Habermas
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] 2015), including in AI-driven administrative contexts where
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] policy is even more distantly embedded in technical code.
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] 619
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] Tacit Consent refers to the implied agreement to political
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] authority
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] inferred
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] from
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] individuals’
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] actions
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] or
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] circumstances, such as residence within a polity, acceptance
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] of its protection, or participation in its institutions (Simmons
[2026-04-04 18:25:58] [stdout] 1993). Although more flexible than explicit consent, it raises
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] enduring questions about voluntariness, awareness, and the
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] possibility of meaningful dissent.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Hobbes suggests continued obedience to the sovereign
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] constitutes acceptance of their authority, even if initial
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] consent was explicit ( Leviathan , ch. XXI). However, in his
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] framework, survival imperatives effectively compel
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] compliance, making tacit consent indistinguishable from
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] submission under necessity. This conflation strips tacit
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] consent of normative force (Pettit 2012), as in automated
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] welfare adjudication where refusal means material
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] deprivation. This limitation highlights Hobbes’s tendency to
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] conflate consent with mere endurance under authority.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Locke offers the most systematic account of tacit consent
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] in Second Treatise of Government (§119–122). He argues
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] that individuals give tacit consent “by actually enjoying any
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] of the dominions of any government,” such as using its
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] infrastructure or holding property under its laws. This form
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] of consent is revocable, and individuals retain the right to
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] exit the polity if dissatisfied (§121). However, Locke’s
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] formulation presupposes realistic alternatives to remaining
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] in the polity, a condition rarely met in practice, as citizens
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] often have no viable opt-out option, thereby undermining
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] the voluntariness central to Lockean tacit consent (Simmons
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] 2000; Tuckness 2009).
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Rousseau is more skeptical of tacit consent as a
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] legitimating mechanism. In The Social Contract , he argues
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] that legitimate political authority must rest on active,
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] ongoing participation in expressing the general will (Book
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] IV). Passive acquiescence or failure to dissent does not
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] constitute consent, as it lacks deliberate political
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] engagement. This view limits Rousseau’s framework in
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] large, complex societies where continuous, meaningful
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] participation is structurally difficult.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Rawls does not frame tacit consent as a central pillar of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] legitimacy, but he does acknowledge that established
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] practices often persist through implicit public acceptance.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] His constructivist approach evaluates such practices by
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] whether they could be justified under fair conditions, rather
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] than by their factual acceptance (Rawls 1971). It shows that
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] his framework grants less normative weight to tacit consent
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] that is sustained by habit rather than reasoned agreement.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Nozick’s minimal state theory implicitly relies on a form
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] of tacit consent through non-resistance to protective
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] associations. Yet, without real opportunities for dissent or
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] withdrawal, such non-resistance may be indistinguishable
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] from imposed compliance (Cohen 2012). This reveals the
