[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Table 1: Legitimacy and Consent in Canonical Social Contract Theories
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] 620
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] limits of his account in settings where individuals cannot
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] meaningfully avoid or reject governance arrangements.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Hypothetical Consent evaluates the legitimacy of political
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] authority by asking whether reasonable individuals, under
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] specified impartial conditions, would agree to the governing
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] arrangements in question. This device is counterfactual and
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] normative rather than empirical, seeking to derive
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] legitimacy from the reasonableness of imagined agreement
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] rather than actual assent.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Hobbes could be read as invoking a proto-form of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] hypothetical consent in his argument that rational
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] individuals, in a pre-political “state of nature,” would agree
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] to submit to an absolute sovereign to escape the “war of all
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] against all” ( Leviathan , ch. XIII). Yet Hobbes’s conditions
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] are so shaped by fear and necessity that they collapse the
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] normative distinction between reasonable agreement and
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] compelled submission (Skinner 2008).
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Locke is more ambivalent about hypothetical consent.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] While he appeals to natural law as binding on all rational
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] creatures, he grounds legitimacy primarily in actual or tacit
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] consent. Nonetheless, Locke occasionally implies that
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] reasonable individuals would consent to governments that
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] protect natural rights, bringing him into limited alignment
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] with hypothetical consent logic (Simmons 2014). This
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] conditional acceptance means Locke’s hypothetical consent
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] applies only to rights-preserving arrangements, limiting its
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] scope in broader governance contexts.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Rousseau’s conception of the “general will” shares a
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] kinship with hypothetical consent insofar as it embodies the
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] collective will of citizens directed toward the common good,
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] which they would endorse under conditions of equal
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] participation. However, Rousseau’s model is less about
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] counterfactual agreement and more about actualized civic
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] authorship. Still, both frameworks rely on the assumption
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] that citizens can deliberate from a standpoint of equality, a
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] condition that could be easily challenged when real-life
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] processes
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] exclude
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] most
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] citizens
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] from
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] meaningful
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] engagement or understanding (Pateman 2015).
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Rawls offers the most influential formulation through the
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] “original position” and “veil of ignorance” in A Theory of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Justice . In this thought experiment, individuals stripped of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] knowledge about their personal characteristics, social status,
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] and natural talents would select principles of justice that
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] maximize fairness and protect the least advantaged (Rawls
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] 1971). Hypothetical consent, here, legitimizes institutions
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] that would be chosen in such fair conditions, regardless of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] actual consent in the real world. However, critics such as
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Mills (2019) contend that Rawls’s idealization risks
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] ignoring entrenched social and technological inequalities.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Nozick explicitly rejects hypothetical consent as a basis
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] for legitimacy. In Anarchy, State, and Utopia (1974), he
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] argues that the fact that people would agree to certain
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] arrangements under imagined conditions does not grant
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] moral permission to impose those arrangements in reality.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Legitimacy, for him, rests on respecting actual entitlements
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] and voluntary associations. This categorical dismissal
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] excludes hypothetical consent as a basis for legitimacy in his
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] theory.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Theoretical Divergences and Limitations
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] in Social Contract Theories
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Despite their foundational influence, these canonical social
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] contract theories exhibit conceptual divergences and
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] internal limitations that complicate their ability to guide
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] contemporary algorithmic governance. These limits appear
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] as both theoretical gaps and normative blind spots in
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] addressing authority that is neither wholly public nor
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] procedurally participatory. Comparative analysis of the five
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] thinkers reveals tensions in their treatments of legitimacy
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] and consent, shaping how their frameworks can or cannot
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] accommodate AI-based decision-making institutions.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] First, there is an unresolved disagreement among theorists
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] regarding the very source of legitimacy. For Hobbes,
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] legitimacy derives from institutional efficacy in preventing
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] conflict and preserving order, where “the value or worth of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] a man is, as of all other things, his price” ( Leviathan , ch. X).
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] His model suppresses any need for recognition-based or
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] moral-substantive legitimacy, which renders it ill-equipped
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] for evaluating AI systems whose harms are neither violent
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] nor visible but operate through opacity and statistical
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] profiling (Eubanks 2018). For example, a Hobbesian
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] government could justify the continuous use of AI-powered
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] risk assessment tools in policing purely on their capacity to
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] lower crime rates, even if they disproportionately target
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] certain communities and erode trust. As Flathman (1993)
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] argues, Hobbes offers a model of authority that is
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] unresponsive to the plural and interpretive moral claims
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] essential to modern democratic legitimacy.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] In contrast, Locke emphasizes the importance of tacit and
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] revocable consent based on the preservation of natural rights.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] However, this reliance on tacit agreement becomes
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] increasingly problematic in digital contexts. Locke’s logic
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] assumes a feasible “right of exit,” which collapses under
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] conditions of platform dependence and infrastructural
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] surveillance. When citizens cannot functionally participate
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] in society without using AI-mediated public services, such
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] as automated tax filing, digital identity verification, or
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] algorithmic welfare distribution, the possibility of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] meaningful exit is effectively nullified. The mere act of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] residing in a jurisdiction or using a digital service is
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] insufficient as a moral basis for binding authority, especially
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] when users have little choice but to comply with embedded
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] algorithmic decisions. Moreover, Locke’s focus on
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] individual property rights as the foundation of political
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] obligation does not anticipate data-based economies, where
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] ownership and agency are frequently decoupled (Cohen
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] 2012). For instance, citizens may have legal ownership of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] personal data in principle but lack any practical control over
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] how AI systems aggregate and process it.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] 621
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Rousseau’s participatory republicanism introduces a
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] more demanding model of legitimacy grounded in collective
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] authorship. His claim that “obedience to the law one
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] prescribes to oneself is freedom” ( The Social Contract ,
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Book I) sets a high normative standard. Yet, this conception
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] is vulnerable to coercive reinterpretation, particularly when
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] “the general will” is operationalized without direct
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] participation or transparency (Berlin 2014). Algorithmic
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] policymaking in environmental regulation, for example,
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] might be defended as serving the collective good but still
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] bypass public input entirely by embedding decisions in
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] technical systems inaccessible to ordinary citizens. In
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] algorithmic regimes, where citizens are neither aware of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] decision-making logics nor consulted in their formulation,
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] the very possibility of being a co-author of the rules
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] becomes
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] illusory.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Contemporary
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] platforms
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] reverse
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Rousseau’s aspiration by automating rule-setting in ways
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] that bypass civic engagement entirely (Zuboff 2019).
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Rawls’s theory of justice, while offering a sophisticated
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] model of hypothetical consent, has also drawn criticism for
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] its abstraction. The veil of ignorance presumes epistemic
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] symmetry and shared moral reasoning, assumptions strained
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] by AI’s hidden architectures and asymmetric information
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] flows (Mills 2019). For example, predictive analytics in
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] healthcare may allocate resources based on biased training
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] data, producing outcomes that those behind the veil of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] ignorance could not rationally endorse if they understood
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] the biases; yet in practice, most stakeholders lack both the
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] access and expertise to evaluate these systems and their
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] complex downstream impacts. Further, this approach does
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] not fully account for how algorithmic personalization
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] fragments the public sphere, undermining the plausibility of
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] shared reasoning upon which his constructivist legitimacy
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] depends (Citron and Pasquale 2014).
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Finally, Nozick’s libertarian minimalism dismisses the
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] need for consent altogether once property rights are
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] respected. His claim that redistributive taxation is equivalent
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] to “forced labor” offers a radically individualist foundation
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] for legitimacy that struggles to accommodate the collective
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] and relational nature of digital infrastructures. In practice,
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] platforms centralize control over user data while diffusing
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] accountability, a form of “infrastructural power” that eludes
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Nozick’s narrow conception of coercion (Cohen 2012). For
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] instance, even if a privately-run AI infrastructure does not
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] explicitly violate property rights, it could still wield
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] enormous de facto power over access to jobs, credit, and
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] public participation, effects that Nozick’s framework is
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] arguably poorly equipped to evaluate.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] What unites these frameworks, despite their divergences,
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] is their limited anticipation of authority that emerges from
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] hybrid, non-state actors, operates across borders, and
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] governs through probabilistic and opaque logics. Modern AI
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] systems, particularly those owned and operated by
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] multinational technology firms, often perform quasi-
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] sovereign functions such as identity verification, credit
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] scoring, and information curation, all without being subject
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] to the institutional legitimacy tests designed for traditional
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] state actors. As Rahwan (2018) notes, algorithmic systems
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] introduce a “machine behavior” paradigm that cuts across
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] traditional political boundaries and ethical theories.
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] Moreover, the reach of the private sector altogether,
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] including its dominance in AI design, implementation, and
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] evaluation, likewise undermines the robustness of any
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] overly state-centric notion of governance. Despite their
[2026-04-04 18:25:59] [stdout] significant contributions then, none of the five thinkers
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] meaningfully engages with (or anticipates) the implications
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] of sustaining political legitimacy within a governance model
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] where authority is often exercised without visibility,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] representation, direct accountability, or even state control.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] This comparative analysis highlights that while the
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] selected theorists offer valuable tools for conceptualizing
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] legitimacy and consent, their models require reinterpretation
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] or supplementation to remain normatively sufficient. Their
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] limitations suggest that AI governance cannot be assessed
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] using these inherited categories alone. Instead, it calls for a
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] reconfiguration of contractarian principles to reflect the
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] structural shifts introduced by computational institutions,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] especially in relation to consent that is rarely explicitly
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] sought and legitimacy that is not publicly deliberated.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Discussion: Implications and
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Normative Strategies for AI Governance
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] The comparative analysis reveals that while classical social
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] contract theories offer diverse and valuable frameworks for
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] assessing legitimacy, none of them, in their original form,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] can fully accommodate the structural and epistemic
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] challenges posed by AI governance. This finding has two
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] major implications: (1) that legitimacy deficits in
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] algorithmic governance are not incidental but structurally
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] embedded in the technology’s design, deployment, and
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] control; and (2) that recalibrating legitimacy will require
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] hybridizing and extending the principles of social contract
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] theory to address these deficits.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Theorizing Legitimacy for the AI Age
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] The first implication concerns the nature of legitimacy in
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] algorithmic contexts. In social contract theory, legitimacy
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] rests on a combination of consent, moral justification, and
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] recognition. However, AI systems often bypass each of
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] these mechanisms: they rarely solicit explicit or tacit
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] consent in meaningful ways; their inner workings are
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] inaccessible, limiting moral evaluation; and they operate
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] invisibly, eroding public recognition of their authority. This
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] suggests that traditional legitimacy tests may need to be
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] reframed in at least three ways:
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] First, subjective legitimacy should be prioritized, even
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] operationalized as an empirical and dynamic measure, i.e.,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] tracking whether affected communities believe algorithmic
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] governance is fair, transparent, and accountable. For
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] 622
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] instance, national health systems using AI for patient triage
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] could incorporate periodic citizen surveys, public audits,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] and community consultations to measure and adjust
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] perceived legitimacy, rather than relying solely on expert
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] assessments of system accuracy or risk acceptance.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Second, consent will need to be reconceptualized for AI-
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] related environments where opting out is practically
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] infeasible. This may require substituting the opportunity for
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] explicit consent with robust procedural safeguards that
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] approximate the conditions under which consent could be
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] given. For example, AI-powered tax compliance systems
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] could include deliberative opt-in windows for major policy
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] changes, allowing citizens to review and challenge new
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] algorithmic rules before implementation.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Third, recognitional legitimacy must be rebuilt through
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] participatory and symbolic inclusion, ensuring that affected
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] citizens identify with the governance process, not merely
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] accept it as inevitable. Along these lines, public-facing
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] dashboards for algorithmic policing or welfare systems
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] could display real-time oversight metrics and community
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] feedback channels, reinforcing the sense that these systems
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] are “of” and “for” the community.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Hybridizing Social Contract Traditions
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] A second implication is that different strands of social
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] contract theory offer complementary resources for AI
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] governance. No single framework can address the multi-
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] layered legitimacy gaps AI introduces. However, a hybrid
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] approach could integrate their respective strengths:
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] • From Hobbes: the recognition that legitimacy requires
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] a clear attribution of responsibility for decision
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] outcomes, even when mediated by complex systems.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] This could support the principle that every AI system in
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] public governance must have a legally accountable
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] authority clearly named.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] • From Locke: the insistence on revocability and the
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] protection of fundamental rights, guiding the design of
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] algorithmic systems with built-in reversibility of
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] decisions where rights are at stake.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] • From Rousseau: the requirement for participatory co-
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] authorship, adapted for digital contexts via citizen
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] assemblies, participatory algorithm design workshops,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] or crowd-sourced policy inputs.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] • From Rawls: the fairness principle as a standard for
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] algorithmic outputs, ensuring that AI systems are tested
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] for disparate impact and, critically, adjusted to meet
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] distributive justice criteria.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] • From Nozick: the minimal coercion principle, reframed
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] to require that citizens retain practical alternatives when
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] interacting with AI systems, especially in contexts such
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] as credit scoring, hiring, and identity verification.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] • Finally, the recalibration of legitimacy should be
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] informed by critical traditions often absent from
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] canonical contract theory, including postcolonial, and
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] intersectional critiques. These perspectives highlight,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] for instance, how many “universal” principles continue
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] to mask structural exclusion and historical injustice.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] AI
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Governance
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Dilemma
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Limitation of Canonical Theories
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Hybrid Principles
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Collective
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Harms vs.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Individual
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Liability
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Hobbes : Oriented toward maintaining order, with limited mechanisms for
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] addressing dispersed or cumulative harms.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Locke : Tacit consent strained in platform-dependence with limited exit options.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Rousseau : Participatory authorship challenged in large-scale, tech-mediated
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] rule-making
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Rawls : Relies on assumptions of transparency and informational symmetry that
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] may not hold in complex AI systems.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Nozick : Lacks tools for addressing collective harms absent direct rights
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] violations.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Hybrid Principle of Distributed
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Accountability: Clear attribution
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] of responsibility (Hobbes) +
