[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Polycentric Legitimacy
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Framework: Integrate local
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] participation (Rousseau),
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] national accountability (Locke),
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] and transnational ethics councils
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] (Rawls) for AI oversight.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Table 2: Hybrid Principles to Address AI Governance Dilemmas
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] 623
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Strategies for Restoring Legitimacy
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Drawing on these hybridized insights, four concrete
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] strategies emerge for recalibrating legitimacy under AI
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] governance:
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] 1. Participatory design and deliberation: AI governance
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] processes should be opened to public participation at
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] design, deployment, and evaluation stages. This might
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] include citizen juries for reviewing high-stakes AI
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] systems, participatory prototyping sessions, and open
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] deliberation on ethical trade-offs. For instance, before
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] rolling out an AI welfare eligibility tool, a government
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] could host multi-stakeholder workshops including
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] recipients, caseworkers, and technologists to jointly
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] review algorithmic decision rules.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] 2. Institutional transparency and algorithmic audits:
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Legitimacy depends on the capacity for public and
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] expert scrutiny. Mandatory independent audits,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] explainability standards, and public disclosure of
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] system objectives and limitations are crucial. For
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] example, predictive policing algorithms could be
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] subject to quarterly independent bias audits, with
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] results made available in public reports.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] 3. Democratic oversight and multi-level accountability:
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Given the transnational nature of many AI systems,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] oversight mechanisms should combine local, national,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] and
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] international
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] layers.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] This
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] could
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] involve
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] transnational ethics councils and local watchdog
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] committees working in conjunction with legislative
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] oversight panels. For example, an international registry
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] of AI systems deployed in public governance could
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] require states to document their purposes, oversight
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] mechanisms, and audit outcomes.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] 4. Pluralistic ethical integration: Since AI governance
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] affects diverse communities, legitimacy should reflect
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] multiple moral perspectives. This means integrating
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] constructivist
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] consent
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] requirements
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] (public
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] justifiability) with fairness tests, rights protections, and
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] minimal coercion safeguards. For instance, an AI-based
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] immigration decision system could be evaluated against
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] both Rawlsian fairness principles and Lockean rights
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] protections, assessing acceptability across different
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] moral doctrines.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Conclusion and Future Directions
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] This paper sets out to examine whether extant approaches to
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] the social contract can stretch to account for the new
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] challenges imposed by AI and the need to govern it. By
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] developing and applying a structured comparative typology
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] of legitimacy (procedural, moral-substantive, recognitional)
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] and consent (explicit, tacit, hypothetical, constructivist), the
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] analysis revealed that while each of the five examined
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] thinkers, including Hobbes, Locke, Rousseau, Rawls, and
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Nozick, offers distinctive insights, none of these canonical
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] approaches can, in isolation, address the multi-layered
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] legitimacy deficits that AI systems introduce.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] The findings demonstrate that these deficits are not
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] accidental but structural. They emerge from the opacity,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] scale, and cross-jurisdictional nature of AI systems, their
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] embedding in private-sector infrastructures, and the
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] practical impossibility for citizens to meaningfully opt out.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] While Hobbesian, Lockean, Rousseauian, Rawlsian, and
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] Nozickian frameworks each capture certain aspects of
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] legitimacy, they leave critical blind spots: Hobbes
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] underestimates moral and recognitional legitimacy, Locke
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] overestimates the feasibility of revocable consent, Rousseau
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] demands participatory structures rarely present in digital
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] governance, Rawls assumes fairness can be evaluated under
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] informational symmetry, and Nozick minimizes the
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] importance of collective oversight.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] The normative strategies proposed here are intended to
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] recalibrate legitimacy for AI governance by hybridizing the
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] strengths of these traditions while compensating for their
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] respective weaknesses. This hybrid framework reframes
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] subjective legitimacy as an ongoing, measurable public
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] perception; reconceptualizes consent for contexts where
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] opting out is unrealistic; and grounds recognitional
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] legitimacy in participatory and symbolic inclusion. Three
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] related avenues for future research are especially urgent:
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] 1. Operationalizing legitimacy: Future work should focus
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] on centering legitimacy normatively as well as
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] developing empirical instruments to measure subjective
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] legitimacy in AI governance contexts. This includes
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] survey-based perception indices, participatory audit
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] logs, and legitimacy dashboards that track trust, fairness,
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] and recognition over time.
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] 2. Embedding consent across AI: Research is needed on
[2026-04-04 18:26:00] [stdout] the technical and institutional mechanisms by which
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] forms of explicit, hypothetical, and constructivist
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] consent can be embedded into AI systems and their
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] governance. For example, dynamic consent protocols
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] could allow citizens to opt in or out of specific data uses
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] over the lifecycle of an AI system.
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] 3. Integrating
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] critical
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] perspectives:
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] Canonical
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] contractarian approaches should be supplemented with
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] feminist, postcolonial, and intersectional analyses to
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] capture how AI governance interacts with existing
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] power asymmetries.
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] In conclusion, the social contract remains a valuable
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] though incomplete lens for interrogating AI governance. Its
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] value lies not in offering a single definitive legitimacy test
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] but in providing a plural set of principles that, when adapted
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] and combined, can illuminate the normative gaps in current
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] governance structures. As AI continues to reshape the
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] conditions under which political authority is exercised, the
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] social contract must itself be renegotiated—expanded to
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] encompass not only the relationship between citizens and
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] the state, but also the algorithmic intermediaries that
[2026-04-04 18:26:01] [stdout] increasingly mediate that relationship.
